metadata.name: NAZCA #85
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

üëΩ Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #36
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Hidden Intersections #424
metadata.description:
In this piece, two grids overlap:

1. a perfect one composed of lines drawn on the screen
2. an irregular one composed of linear zones that reference other parts of the screen

Everything you see in the final composition is a result of the overlapping intersections of these two grids with each other, and eventually themselves.


------------

Created as part of #genuaryTogether for #genuary2023, for the 4th day, theme: "intersections".

source code: https://github.com/protozoo/genuary23_04_intersections

controls:
- "s" key: save a png of the display
- "w" key: generate and save a 4k widescreen version of your seed (it will look different, but always be the same)

metadata.name: Zusammen #104
metadata.description:
The flow of colors across an infinitely maleable grid. Zusammen is built using a framebuffer setup in p5js sampling a rendered direction field to determine the pixel "push" direction, speed, and offsets.

You can run this in fullscreen as instructed below. Doing so will render at the browser's width and height, which will look quite different from the preview version, but will still use the same colors and rules as your token. This can be useful for making wallpapers etc.

You can also continue to run the simulation after it has stopped by hitting the spacebar. This will allow you to further explore the infinite generative space of the piece.

Made with p5js.

Double click to download
Add &highres=true to the URL to get a higher resolution output
Add &fullscreen=true to render to the browser size. N.B. outputs will be somewhat different than the regular view

license information in license.md

metadata.name: The Way of Thinking #10
metadata.description:
How do thoughts form and evolve? Do they harmonize or stand alone? Do they collide or coalesce? In "The Way of Thinking" I‚Äôve tried to capture the essence of thought ‚Äî the raw genesis, the dynamic transformation, and the interplay of associations in the mind's labyrinthine corridors.

I was longly inspired by the strict bounds of math and physics. Now it‚Äôs a time to set myself free into an unpredictable organic world. This artwork is my first exploration of differential growth algorithms where each particle moves, interacts with others, and multiplies as thoughts in our minds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience. Chrome is highly recommended for high res saving.

Made with love and p5js.


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG at current resolution
[2] - save PNG 5000 x 5000
[3] - save PNG 5000 x 5000 without grain

metadata.name: #2023Streams #136
metadata.description:
#2023Streams is a color theory study that explores the use of algorithmically-generated color palettes and the juxtaposition of color harmonies keyed on a common hue. It brings playfulness to experimentation through the use of randomized features that control lighting, color assortment, and more, to create interesting, vibrant compositions.

I consider this piece‚Äîmy generative "genesis"‚Äîto be a preliminary "sketch" whose desired outcomes are insights into color and light that might be applied to more advanced projects in the future.

This piece is also a first step for me, into the world of professional art. An art school dropout and software engineer by profession, I've been hacking on generative art projects, games, and interactive experiences for more than two decades. But now, in 2023, it's my time to focus and prioritize art and creativity.

Each image can be modified using the following keyboard commands:
- [d] Download the rendered image
- [j] Toggle between "jungle" (dimensional) and "jazz" (flat) modes
- [l] Toggle between light and dark backgrounds
- [e] Toggle between curved (ellipse) and flat (rectangle) shapes
- [s] Enable/disable shadows and highlights
- [t] Enable/disable transparency

Each image is rendered at 2400 x 2400 pixels by default. This should be suitable for an 8" x 8" output (at 300 dpi). Should you desire a higher resolution output, the image can be magnified up to 6x by clicking the "open ‚ÜóÔ∏è" link and appending a density parameter to the URL, e.g. `&density=4` 

Lastly, #2023Streams is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license. This license allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build upon the material in any medium or format, so long as attribution is given to the creator. The license allows for commercial use.

What does this license mean? It means I invite you to have fun with your new piece, get creative and bring something new into the world.

I hope you enjoy these outputs as much as I do. Thank you for stopping by‚Äîand hopefully collecting.

metadata.name: WRAPPERS #81
metadata.description:
Generative animated artwork made using shader feedback and pixel quantization.

WRAPPERS is a study of virtual surfaces and textures. It explores the tension between hard and soft forms and parallel projection, where the illusion of perspective is flattened into a highly geometric composition. These geometries feature a flowing texture that runs infinitely, reflecting on the endless nature of virtual space. The project blends together imagery from early computer terminals, video games, and ascii art to produce a dynamic, intricate, visual experience.

WRAPPERS is very GPU intensive. For a smoother experience, you can change the scale by adding the parameter "?scale=2" to the URL.

Press 'i' to invert the colors.
Press '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6' to scale the bitmap glyphs.
Press 'g' to download a looping animated GIF (150 frames). Please make sure to let the animation run for at least 30 seconds first.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Press 'f' (or double tap in mobile) to stretch to full screen.
Made with vanilla javascript and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: <iframes> #9
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110
